#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:142
#, no-wrap
msgid "Communication Layer (TCP/IP Network)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:146
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"A cluster requires a communication layer to interconnect the slave nodes to\n"
"the master node. Typically, a FastEthernet or GigaEthernet LAN can be used\n"
"since they have a good price/performance ratio. Other possibilities include\n"
"use of products like <uri link=\"http://www.myricom.com/\">Myrinet</uri>, <uri\n"
"link=\"http://quadrics.com/\">QsNet</uri> or others.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:154
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"A cluster is composed of two node types: master and slave. Typically, your\n"
"cluster will have one master node and several slave nodes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:159
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The master node is the cluster's server. It is responsible for telling the\n"
"slave nodes what to do. This server will typically run such daemons as dhcpd,\n"
"nfs, pbs-server, and pbs-sched. Your master node will allow interactive\n"
"sessions for users, and accept job executions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:166
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The slave nodes listen for instructions (via ssh/rsh perhaps) from the master\n"
"node. They should be dedicated to crunching results and therefore should not\n"
"run any unnecessary services.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:172
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The rest of this documentation will assume a cluster configuration as per the\n"
"hosts file below. You should maintain on every node such a hosts file\n"
"(<path>/etc/hosts</path>) with entries for each node participating node in the\n"
"cluster.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:178
#, no-wrap
msgid "/etc/hosts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:179
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# Adelie Linux Research &amp; Development Center\n"
"# /etc/hosts\n"
"\n"
"127.0.0.1       localhost\n"
"\n"
"192.168.1.100   master.adelie master\n"
"\n"
"192.168.1.1     node01.adelie node01\n"
"192.168.1.2     node02.adelie node02\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:191
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To setup your cluster dedicated LAN, edit your <path>/etc/conf.d/net</path>\n"
"file on the master node.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:195
#, no-wrap
msgid "/etc/conf.d/net"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:196
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# Global config file for net.* rc-scripts\n"
"\n"
"# This is basically the ifconfig argument without the ifconfig $iface\n"
"#\n"
"\n"
"iface_eth0=\"192.168.1.100 broadcast 192.168.1.255 netmask 255.255.255.0\"\n"
"# Network Connection to the outside world using dhcp -- configure as required for you network\n"
"iface_eth1=\"dhcp\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:208
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Finally, setup a DHCP daemon on the master node to avoid having to maintain a\n"
"network configuration on each slave node.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:212
#, no-wrap
msgid "/etc/dhcp/dhcpd.conf"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:213
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# Adelie Linux Research &amp; Development Center\n"
"# /etc/dhcp/dhcpd.conf\n"
"\n"
"log-facility local7;\n"
"ddns-update-style none;\n"
"use-host-decl-names on;\n"
"\n"
"subnet 192.168.1.0 netmask 255.255.255.0 {\n"
"        option domain-name \"adelie\";\n"
"        range 192.168.1.10 192.168.1.99;\n"
"        option routers 192.168.1.100;\n"
"\n"
"        host node01.adelie {\n"
"                # MAC address of network card on node 01\n"
"                hardware ethernet 00:07:e9:0f:e2:d4;\n"
"                fixed-address 192.168.1.1;\n"
"        }\n"
"        host node02.adelie {\n"
"                # MAC address of network card on node 02\n"
"                hardware ethernet 00:07:e9:0f:e2:6b;\n"
"                fixed-address 192.168.1.2;\n"
"        }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:241
#, no-wrap
msgid "NFS/NIS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:245
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The Network File System (NFS) was developed to allow machines to mount a disk\n"
"partition on a remote machine as if it were on a local hard drive. This allows\n"
"for fast, seamless sharing of files across a network.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:251
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are other systems that provide similar functionality to NFS which could\n"
"be used in a cluster environment. The <uri\n"
"link=\"http://www.openafs.org\">Andrew File System\n"
"from IBM</uri>, recently open-sourced, provides a file sharing mechanism with\n"
"some additional security and performance features. The <uri\n"
"link=\"http://www.coda.cs.cmu.edu/\">Coda File System</uri> is still in\n"
"development, but is designed to work well with disconnected clients. Many\n"
"of the features of the Andrew and Coda file systems are slated for inclusion\n"
"in the next version of <uri link=\"http://www.nfsv4.org\">NFS (Version 4)</uri>.\n"
"The advantage of NFS today is that it is mature, standard, well understood,\n"
"and supported robustly across a variety of platforms.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:264
#, no-wrap
msgid "Ebuilds for NFS-support"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/hpc-howto.xml:265
#, no-wrap
